US civilian deaths from police officers in one year¶

Hui Wang

Overview¶

There are thousands of US civilians killed by police officers for almost every year. It is important to be aware of the numbers of deaths and the data behind them. From that, this tutorial introduces a deep analysis on US civilian deaths from police officers in 2016. The tutorial includes three main parts. The first part will include data collecting and data cleaning processes. The second part will demonstrate how to analyze the given data and display visualization. The third part will come up with a linear regression model to process the analysis and verify the hypotheses implied from it.

Tools¶

  • pandas
  • numpy
  • scikit-learn
  • matplotlib
  • folium

For the dataset, the homicide reports data can be retrived at https://www.kaggle.com/the-guardian/the-counted#2016.csv

The first thing I need to do is download the dataset at https://www.kaggle.com/the-guardian/the-counted#2016.csv. The file downloaded will be in form of a CSV called 2016.csv. Then, I need to apply pandas libraries to help me initialize the data in nice frames and columns.

Part 2: Data Analysis and Visualization¶

Now, the data is ready to be analyzed. In this part, I would like to visualize the data with some plots and map in order to see the relations for each category with the number of deaths.

2.1 Number of Deaths By Age¶

First thing I would like to analyze is the number of deaths happened at different ages.

2.1.1 Extract the Number of Deaths with Age¶

I apply pandas function "groupby()" and "count()" to create a new dataframe that count the number of deaths for each provided age.

In [5]:
#Use groupby and count functions to count the number of deaths at any age
data_by_age = data.copy().groupby(data['age'], as_index=True, group_keys=True).count()
#Put another column that later will be replaced by counts.
count_by_age = data_by_age[['gender']].reset_index()
#Replace gender with number
count_by_age = count_by_age.rename(index=str, columns={'gender' : 'number'})

#Convert all ages from str to int for later calculation
for i in range(0,len(count_by_age)):
    count_by_age['age'][i] = int(count_by_age['age'][i])

Part 3: Linear Regression and Hypothesis Test¶

Now I will use linear regression and test my predictions. When doing a linear regression, I'm taking data that is already there and predicting future data base on the patterns of the data I already have. I will take a linear regression of Number of Deaths vs Age data and compare it to another regression when taking account of states using a f test. And I predict that if we can account many factors, I will be able to have more accurate predictions.

3.1 Linear Regression on Number of Deaths by Age¶

I will use the Linear Regression model library to create the model and to get our predicted values.

A short tutorial of linear regression can be found at: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/linear_model/plot_ols.html

In [17]:
#Linear Regression
reg = linear_model.LinearRegression()
X = [[x] for x in count_by_age['age'].values]
Y = [[y] for y in count_by_age['number'].values]
regfit = reg.fit(X, Y)

#Get predcited Values
pred = []
for x in count_by_age['age'].values:
    pred.append(regfit.predict(x)[0][0])
count_by_age['pred'] = pd.Series(pred, index = count_by_age.index)

#Plot the linear regression line with the data
plt.plot(count_by_age['age'], count_by_age['number'])
plt.plot(count_by_age['age'], count_by_age['pred'], color='red')
plt.xlabel("age")
plt.ylabel("number")
plt.title("deaths vs age with Linear Regression")

3.2 Fitting the Linear Regression Model¶

I will group the data by age and State so that I can get the number of deaths associated with those columns. Next I will fit the data to the linear regression model. In order to do this I will use the ols regression library to retrieve the linear regression formula.

I would like to fit two different linear regressions. First is the regression with count associate with age. Second is the regression with both age and state.

3.3 Hypothesis Testing¶

In order to verify the hypothesis, I will apply f-test. The purpose of this test is to verify my linear regression models fit the data well. I will also utilize the statsmodels library to calculate the f-test.

The tutorial of f-test can be found at: https://www.statisticshowto.datasciencecentral.com/probability-and-statistics/hypothesis-testing/f-test/.

The tutorial of anova function from the statsmodels library can be found at: https://www.marsja.se/four-ways-to-conduct-one-way-anovas-using-python/

Based on the f-test of the two linear regression models, the PR(>F) of the regression model that takes both age and state has a really small value. Therefore the model that takes both age and state as a factor will provide me the most accurate predictions.

Conclusion¶

I believe it is important to be aware of how many people are killed by police officers because it could show the currect criminal condition of the soceity. The tutorial could show to the audience that the factors behind the number of deaths from police officer.

Base on the analysis, I can conclude that the number of deaths differ the most by age and state. I can also conclude that as the age increases the number of deaths from police officer decreases. It can also be seen that in the more populous states such as California and Texas, death from police officer happen more frequently. Moreover, more male were killed than female and more armed people were killed than non-armed people.

Therefore, it is cruical to take many factors into account when you are considering the data of civilian deaths from police officers.
